# ADR-0001: Language and Framework Choice

## Status

Accepted

## Context

{{ display_name }} is a new CLI tool: {{ description }}

We needed to select an implementation language and a CLI framework. The following requirements
guided the decision:

- Distribute as: **{{ distribution }}**
- Target users are developers comfortable with a terminal
- The tool may be invoked in scripts and CI pipelines, so predictable exit codes and machine-readable output are required
- The codebase should be approachable for contributors familiar with the chosen language

### Options Evaluated

#### Languages

| Language | Strengths | Weaknesses |
|----------|-----------|------------|
| Python | Fast iteration, large library ecosystem, easy scripting | Requires runtime; distribution of executables is complex |
| Go | Compiles to static binary, fast startup, good stdlib | Verbose error handling; less ergonomic for argument parsing |
| Rust | Best performance, memory safety, excellent binary output | Steep learning curve; slower compile times |
| TypeScript | Familiar for web developers, rich ecosystem | Requires Node.js runtime; startup time higher than compiled |

#### CLI Frameworks

| Framework | Language | Strengths |
|-----------|----------|-----------|
| Typer | Python | Type-annotation-first, auto-generates help, integrates with Rich |
| Click | Python | Mature, flexible, decorator-based, well-documented |
| Cobra | Go | De facto Go CLI standard, used by kubectl and many major tools |
| Clap | Rust | Derive-macro ergonomics, excellent validation, shell completions |
| Commander | TypeScript/Node | Most widely used Node CLI library, flexible |

## Decision

We chose **{{ language }}** with **{{ cli_framework }}**.

{% if language == "python" and cli_framework == "typer" %}
### Rationale

**Python** was selected because the team has strong Python experience and the tool's logic
benefits from Python's rich ecosystem of libraries. Distribution as a pip package is
well-understood and widely supported.

**Typer** was selected over Click because:

- Commands map directly to typed Python functions - less boilerplate
- Help text, types, and defaults are derived from function signatures
- First-class integration with [Rich](https://github.com/Textualize/rich) for formatted output
- Typer is built on Click, so Click patterns apply when needed

{% elif language == "python" and cli_framework == "click" %}
### Rationale

**Python** was selected for the team's existing expertise and the tool's library requirements.

**Click** was selected over Typer because:

- More explicit control over argument and option definitions
- Wider community familiarity and larger body of examples
- Stable, battle-tested API
- No dependency on type annotation conventions

{% elif language == "go" and cli_framework == "cobra" %}
### Rationale

**Go** was selected because the tool is distributed as a static binary and needs fast startup
time for use in shell scripts and CI pipelines. The single-binary distribution model eliminates
runtime dependency management for end users.

**Cobra** was selected because:

- It is the industry standard for Go CLIs (kubectl, Helm, GitHub CLI all use it)
- Strong subcommand support with automatic help generation
- Built-in shell completion support (bash, zsh, fish, PowerShell)
- Integrates with Viper for config file handling

{% elif language == "rust" and cli_framework == "clap" %}
### Rationale

**Rust** was selected because performance and correctness are top priorities. The tool may
process large inputs or run in resource-constrained environments. Static compilation produces
a zero-dependency binary.

**Clap** was selected because:

- Derive macros produce ergonomic, self-documenting argument structs
- Compile-time validation of argument definitions
- Best-in-class shell completion generation
- Active development and first-party support in the Rust ecosystem

{% elif language == "typescript" and cli_framework == "commander" %}
### Rationale

**TypeScript** was selected because the team has deep JavaScript/TypeScript expertise and
the tool shares logic with an existing Node.js codebase.

**Commander** was selected because:

- Widest adoption in the Node CLI ecosystem
- Minimal, predictable API
- First-class TypeScript support
- No magic - explicit option and command registration

{% else %}
### Rationale

**{{ language }}** was selected because it best fits the team's expertise, the distribution
model ({{ distribution }}), and the tool's performance requirements.

**{{ cli_framework }}** was selected because it is the most ergonomic and well-maintained
CLI framework available for {{ language }}.
{% endif %}

### Distribution: {{ distribution }}

{% if distribution == "pip-package" %}
Distributing as a PyPI package allows users to install with `pip install {{ project_name }}`
or `pipx install {{ project_name }}`. This is the standard Python CLI distribution method
and integrates with existing Python toolchains.
{% elif distribution == "binary" %}
Distributing as a pre-compiled binary removes any runtime dependency for users. Binaries are
cross-compiled for Linux, macOS (amd64 and arm64), and Windows using CI. Users download
from GitHub Releases.
{% elif distribution == "homebrew" %}
Homebrew is the dominant package manager for macOS developers and is widely used on Linux.
A Homebrew formula allows `brew install {{ project_name }}` with automatic update support.
{% elif distribution == "docker" %}
Docker distribution ensures a fully reproducible, dependency-free runtime. The image is
published to a container registry and users run the tool with `docker run`. This is
particularly useful for CI pipeline usage.
{% endif %}

## Consequences

### Positive

{% if language == "python" %}
- Rapid iteration; new commands can be added in minutes
- Full access to Python package ecosystem
- Easy local development setup (`pip install -e ".[dev]"`)
{% elif language == "go" %}
- Single static binary with no runtime dependencies
- Fast startup time suitable for shell aliases and scripts
- Cross-compilation to all major platforms from a single CI job
{% elif language == "rust" %}
- Zero-cost abstractions and memory safety without a GC
- Extremely fast startup and execution
- Deterministic binary size and performance
{% elif language == "typescript" %}
- Shared code with existing Node.js services
- Large npm ecosystem for parsing, formatting, and networking
- Familiar toolchain for the team
{% endif %}

### Negative

{% if language == "python" %}
- End users must have Python installed (mitigated by pipx or binary packaging with PyInstaller)
- Startup time is higher than compiled languages
- Virtual environment management adds local dev friction
{% elif language == "go" %}
- More verbose error handling than scripting languages
- Larger binary size than Rust for small tools
- Less ergonomic string manipulation
{% elif language == "rust" %}
- Longer compile times slow down CI and local iteration
- Steeper learning curve for new contributors
- Smaller talent pool than Python or Go
{% elif language == "typescript" %}
- Requires Node.js runtime (typically not an issue for developer tools)
- Startup time includes Node.js and module loading
- Build step required before distribution
{% endif %}

### Risks

- If the distribution model changes later (e.g., from pip to binary), the build pipeline
  will need to be redesigned.
- Adding a new command that requires a heavy dependency should trigger a new ADR to assess
  the impact on binary size or install footprint.

